## Step 2 — Generate the diagram

### 2A. Sequence diagrams from workflow code

Read the workflow Go file and trace:
1. The entry point function (e.g., `CreatePoolWorkflow`)
2. All `workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, struct.Method, args...)` calls in execution order
3. Child workflow invocations via `workflow.ExecuteChildWorkflow`
4. Conditional branches (`if`/`else`) that select different activity paths
5. Loops over collections
6. Signal handling (`workflow.GetSignalChannel`, `Receive`)

**Standard participants** (use these aliases consistently):

```
participant Client
participant GoogleProxy as Google Proxy
participant CoreAPI as Core API
participant Orchestrator
participant Workflow as <Resource> Workflow
participant Activities as <Resource> Activities
participant CommonAct as Common Activities
participant DB as Database
participant ONTAP as ONTAP
participant VLMClient as VLM Client
participant VLM as VLM Service
participant Temporal
participant GCP as Google Cloud
```

Only include participants that appear in the traced flow. Use `as` aliases for readability.

**Sequence diagram conventions:**
- Solid arrow `A->>B:` for synchronous calls
- Dashed arrow `B-->>A:` for responses
- `Note over A,B:` for phase annotations
- `alt`/`else`/`end` for conditional branches
- `loop` for iterations
- `opt` for optional steps
- `activate`/`deactivate` sparingly — only for long-running operations

**Example structure:**

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Client
    participant Workflow as Create Pool Workflow
    participant Activities as Pool Activities
    participant DB as Database
    participant ONTAP as ONTAP

    Client->>Workflow: CreatePoolWorkflow(params)
    Workflow->>Activities: CreateJob(job)
    Activities->>DB: INSERT job
    DB-->>Activities: Job created
    Activities-->>Workflow: Job

    Workflow->>Activities: CreateGCPResources(params)
    Activities->>GCP: Provision infrastructure
    GCP-->>Activities: Resources ready
    Activities-->>Workflow: Success

    alt Success
        Workflow->>Activities: UpdateJobStatus(DONE)
    else Failure
        Workflow->>Activities: UpdateJobStatus(ERROR)
    end
```

### 2B. State diagrams from lifecycle constants

Read the model file and identify:
1. State constants (e.g., `LifeCycleStateCreating`, `LifeCycleStateREADY`)
2. State transitions implied by workflow code (create sets CREATING, success sets READY, etc.)
3. Error and recovery paths

**State diagram conventions:**
- Use `---\ntitle: <Title>\n---` frontmatter for titled diagrams
- Use `[*]` for initial and terminal states
- Transition labels: `Event` or `Condition`
- Use `note right of STATE` for explanatory notes

**Example:**

```mermaid
---
title: Volume Lifecycle State Transitions
---
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> CREATING: Create Request
    CREATING --> READY: Success
    CREATING --> ERROR: Creation Failed
    READY --> UPDATING: Update Request
    READY --> DELETING: Delete Request
    UPDATING --> READY: Success
    UPDATING --> ERROR: Update Failed
    DELETING --> DELETED: Success
    DELETING --> ERROR: Deletion Failed
    ERROR --> READY: Recovery
    ERROR --> DELETING: Force Delete
    DELETED --> [*]
```

### 2C. ER diagrams from GORM models

Read the datamodel Go structs and extract:
1. Struct fields with GORM tags (`gorm:"column:..."`)
2. Primary keys, unique keys, foreign keys
3. Relationships (`gorm:"ForeignKey:..."`, embedded structs, slice fields)
4. JSON/JSONB columns

**ER diagram conventions:**
- Use `PK` for primary keys, `FK` for foreign keys, `UK` for unique keys
- Map Go types: `string`, `int64`, `bool`, `timestamp` (for `time.Time`), `jsonb` (for JSONB/JSON fields)
- Relationship notation: `||--o{` (one-to-many), `||--||` (one-to-one), `}o--o{` (many-to-many)

**Example:**

```mermaid
erDiagram
    Pool {
        int64 ID PK
        string UUID UK
        string Name
        string State
        int64 AccountID FK
        jsonb BuildInfo
        timestamp CreatedAt
    }

    Volume {
        int64 ID PK
        string UUID UK
        string Name
        int64 PoolID FK
        int64 SizeInBytes
    }

    Pool ||--o{ Volume : contains
    Pool ||--o| Account : belongs_to
```

### 2D. Architecture diagrams

For component/system architecture, use `graph TB` (top-to-bottom) or `graph LR` (left-to-right):

**Conventions:**
- Group related components in `subgraph` blocks with descriptive labels
- Use short, clear node labels
- Database nodes use `[( )]` cylinder shape: `DB[(Database)]`
- External services use standard rectangles
- Direction arrows show data/control flow

**Example:**

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph clientLayer [Client Layer]
        API[Google Cloud API]
    end

    subgraph controlPlane [VSA Control Plane]
        GP[Google Proxy]
        Core[Core API]
        Worker[VCP Worker]
        Temporal[Temporal Server]
    end

    subgraph dataLayer [Data Layer]
        VCP[(VCP Database)]
        Metrics[(Metrics Database)]
    end

    subgraph external [External Services]
        ONTAP[ONTAP Storage]
        VLM[VLM Service]
        GCP[Google Cloud]
    end

    API --> GP
    GP --> Core
    Core --> Worker
    Worker --> Temporal
    Worker --> VCP
    Worker --> ONTAP
    Worker --> VLM
    Worker --> GCP
```

### 2E. Flowcharts for decision logic

Use `flowchart TD` for branching/decision flows:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    Start([Start]) --> CheckState{Pool State?}
    CheckState -->|READY| Proceed[Proceed with operation]
    CheckState -->|CREATING| Wait[Wait for pool]
    CheckState -->|DELETED| Reject[Reject request]
    CheckState -->|ERROR| Evaluate{Retriable?}
    Evaluate -->|Yes| Retry[Retry operation]
    Evaluate -->|No| Fail[Return error]
    Proceed --> Done([Done])
    Retry --> CheckState
```

