## Code analysis reference

When generating diagrams from code, read these source locations:

| What to diagram | Where to look |
|----------------|---------------|
| Workflow flows | `core/orchestrator/workflows/` — trace `ExecuteActivity`, `ExecuteChildWorkflow` |
| Activity details | `core/orchestrator/activities/` — trace external calls, DB ops |
| Data models | `core/datamodel/models.go` (alias: `database/vcp/datamodel/`) |
| Lifecycle states | `core/models/` — `LifeCycleState*` constants |
| API endpoints | `core/core-api/endpoints/` — request/response flow |
| Factory orchestration | `core/orchestrator/factory/gcp/` or `oci/` — how operations are initiated |
| Hyperscaler calls | `hyperscaler/` — cloud provider abstractions |
| Cancellation flow | `core/orchestrator/common/cancellation.go` — signal/rollback pattern |
| Supervisor pattern | `core/tasks/workflow_supervisor_task.go` — job monitoring |

---

## Communication style
- Show the diagram immediately — don't describe it first.
- If the diagram is large, break it into multiple focused diagrams rather than one monolithic one.
- If generating from code and the source file is ambiguous, list the candidates and ask which one to diagram.
- For sequence diagrams, aim for 15-40 interactions. If the workflow has more, split into phases (pre-processing, main flow, cleanup).
- Use the standard participant aliases consistently across all diagrams.
